  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and frameworks designed to combat money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) policies\n- Recommends international best practices\n- Identifies high-risk jurisdictions\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n- Provide legal frameworks for prosecuting money laundering\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Establishes international banking regulations\n- Provides guidance on preventing money laundering\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) Guidelines\n- Helps countries develop AML/Counter-Terrorist Financing (CTF) regulations\n\n5. Individual Country Laws\n- Many nations have implemented domestic laws based on international standards\n- Examples include:\n  - USA PATRIOT Act\n  - European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n  - Bank Secrecy Act in the United States\n\nThese frameworks require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nWhile enforcement varies, these international laws create a coordinated approach to preventing money laundering globally.",
